  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Why astronauts have a white and an orange-coloured space suit?",
  "response": "Astronauts have different colored space suits, primarily white and orange, for specific functional and safety reasons:\n\n1. **White Space Suits:**\n   - **Temperature Regulation:** White suits are primarily used for spacewalks (extravehicular activities or EVAs) because white reflects heat and sunlight, helping to keep astronauts cool in the harsh environment of space. The temperature in space can fluctuate dramatically, and white is the most effective color for maintaining a stable internal temperature.\n   - **Visibility:** White also provides good visibility against the dark backdrop of space, making it easier for astronauts to see each other and for mission control to monitor them.\n\n2. **Orange Space Suits (Advanced Crew Escape Suits, ACES):**\n   - **Emergency Visibility:** The bright orange color is used for the launch and re-entry phases of space missions. This vibrant color makes astronauts highly visible, which is crucial during emergencies, such as an escape from the spacecraft. The bright color can be easily spotted against various backgrounds, including water, land, or the spacecraft itself.\n   - **Protection During Launch and Re-entry:** These suits, also known as \"pumpkin suits,\" offer protection against the extreme conditions experienced during launch and re-entry, including depressurization and temperature changes. They are equipped with necessary survival gear, such as parachutes and life vests, in case of an emergency landing in water.\n\nIn summary, the different colors of space suits are chosen based on the specific requirements of the mission phase: white for spacewalks to regulate temperature and enhance visibility in space, and orange for launch and re-entry to ensure high visibility and safety during potential emergencies.",
